            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="33411151">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">本来准备看书，但是这么难的书，据说中文版的翻译很悲催，英文版实在难啃，先找个同款视频打打底。写个只有自己能看清楚脉络的读书笔记。

1. Dilemma
救1个还是救5个？
火车司机，面对两个轨道，一个有一个工人，一个有五个工人？
医生，手术，会选择救五个去牺牲另一个？

2.Two different modes of moral reasoning

2.1 Consequentialist moral reasoning结果主义
locates morality in the consequences of an act
...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2014-11-14 14:59</span>
                  
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="">1人喜欢</span>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                本来准备看书，但是这么难的书，据说中文版的翻译很悲催，英文版实在难啃，先找个同款视频打打底。写个只有自己能看清楚脉络的读书笔记。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1. Dilemma<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>救1个还是救5个？<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>火车司机，面对两个轨道，一个有一个工人，一个有五个工人？<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>医生，手术，会选择救五个去牺牲另一个？<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2.Two different modes of moral reasoning<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2.1 Consequentialist moral reasoning结果主义<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>locates morality in the consequences of an act<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The most influential example of consequential moral reasoning is Utilitarianism, a doctrine invented by Jeremy Bentham, the 18th century English political philosopher<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>结果主义最著名的例子是功利主义，由边沁提出，他是18世纪英国的一名政治哲学家。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2.2 Categorical moral reasonin绝对主义<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>locates morality in certain categorical duties and rights<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>道德有其绝对的道德原则，有明确的职责好，明确的权利，不论后果是怎样<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The most important philosopher of categorically moral reasoningis the 18th century German philosopher Immanuel Kant 18世纪德国的哲学家，康德<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>3.课程内容：<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Book list : Aristotle亚里士多德, John Locke洛克, Immanuel Kant, John Stuart Mill约翰.密尔<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Take up contemporary political and legal controversy tat raise philosophical questions  讨论当代政治和法律争议,讨论它们背后的哲学问题<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Debate equality and inequality, affirmative action平权行动， free speech vs hate speech言论自由， 攻击性言论，same sex marriage， military conscription征兵。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>4.Risks:  <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Philosophy teaches us and unsettles us by confronting us with what we already know<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Philosophy distances us from conventions, from estabilished assumptions , from settle beliefs (哲学确实会让我们疏远我们过去的惯例习俗，预定的假设，固有的观念)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>At the face of these risks, there's a characteristic evasion. The name of the evasion is scepticsm面对这些风险，我们有一个特别的回避方式。回避方式叫怀疑主义。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>We didn't resolve once for all<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>我们不会彻底地解决问题。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>But these questions are unavoidable. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Scepticism just throwig up your hands, and given up by moral reflection is no solution<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>因此，怀疑主义只是让你放手，放弃思考道德问题并不是问题的答案。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Scepticism is a resting place for human reasonin where it can relect on dogmatic wandering, but it is no dwelling place for permanent settlement. Simply to asquiesce, scepticism can't never suffice to overcome the recklessness f reason<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>它只是让我们在一些教条之间徘徊，它不是我们最好的安息之。怀疑主义只是简单的默许，它不足以经受住“鲁莽”的推理。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>5. 课程目的：<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The end of this course is to awaken recklessnes of reason and to see where I might lead<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>本课程的目的是唤醒我们鲁莽的推理，然后看看我们最后会走到哪里。
